IGF::OT::IGF THE PROPOSED INNOVATION IS A METHODOLOGY FOR ADVANCED PROCESS CONTROL AND DEPOSITION ANALYSIS BUILT AROUND USING SIGNALS GENERATED BY BEAM-COMPONENT INTERACTIONS IN THE ELECTRON BEAM FREE FORM FABRICATION (EBF3) SYSTEM. BASED UPON OUR SUCCESSFUL PHASE I RESULTS, THESE SIGNALS HAVE THE POTENTIAL TO BE USED FOR MANY FORMS OF BOTH METROLOGY AND PROCESS CONTROL. WHILE MANY MATERIAL PROPERTIES MIGHT BE STUDIED BY USING THIS INTERACTION, OUR INITIAL FOCUS IS AN INVESTIGATION INTO BEAM AND SENSOR CHARACTERISTICS FOR GEOMETRIC ANALYSIS OF THE DEPOSITION. SIGNALS DERIVED FROM THE ELECTRON BEAM-COMPONENT INTERACTION COULD OFFER SPATIALLY RESOLVED DIMENSIONAL INFORMATION ABOUT THE DEPOSITED MATERIAL, AS IT IS BEING DEPOSITED. THIS IS IMPORTANT, AS THE ABILITY TO MONITOR A PARAMETER DURING DEPOSITION CREATES THE POSSIBILITY OF CONTROLLING THAT PARAMETER DURING THE DEPOSITION PROCESS. AS A FURTHER REFINEMENT, THE ABILITY TO COLLECT AND STORE A SPATIALLY RESOLVED PASS-BY-PASS MAP OF THE DEPOSITION PATH GEOMETRY MAY HAVE VALUE IN ON-THE-FLY ADJUSTMENTS TO SUBSEQUENT BUILD PASSES. SUCH MAPPING WOULD ALLOW WORKING WITH THE LAYER-BY-LAYER NATURE OF THE DEPOSITION PROCESS TO FINE TUNE THE DEPOSITION GEOMETRY. SUCH SPATIALLY RESOLVED, LAYER-BY-LAYER DEPOSITION MAPPING COULD ALSO BE STORED, GIVING A THREE DIMENSIONAL MAPPING OF THE AS-BUILT DEPOSITION PATH GEOMETRY. THIS COULD PROVE VALUABLE FOR COMPONENT QUALITY ASSURANCE.

COASTAL UPWELLING IS AN IMPORTANT FACTOR IN AIR-SEA HEAT EXCHANGE IN COASTAL AREAS, COASTAL WEATHER AND CLIMATE, AND COASTAL ECOSYSTEM AND FISHERY HEALTH. FUTURE ATMOSPHERIC CLIMATE CHANGE, THROUGH A SHIFT IN ATMOSPHERIC CIRCULATION AND WIND STRESS, MAY AFFECT COASTAL OCEAN UPWELLING DYNAMICS, BUT THE PREDICTED OCEANIC RESPONSE IS STILL NOT WELL CONSTRAINED. THUS, THERE IS A PRESSING NEED TO IMPROVE OUR UNDERSTANDING AND PREDICTIVE SKILL OF COASTAL OCEANIC UPWELLING VARIABILITY AND HOW IT MAY CHANGE IN THE FUTURE. WE PROPOSE TO STUDY THE POTENTIAL FOR CHANGES IN COASTAL UPWELLING IN RESPONSE TO CLIMATE CHANGE. THE PROPOSED STUDY IS DIVIDED INTO THREE PARTS: FIRST, MAKING USE OF EXISTING SATELLITE DATASETS TO IMPROVE OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE PHYSICAL CONNECTION BETWEEN MODERN CLIMATE OR ATMOSPHERIC VARIABILITY AND UPWELLING VARIABILITY ON INTERANNUAL TIME SCALES; SECOND, A PROCESS MODEL STUDY OF THE POTENTIAL FOR ABRUPT SHIFTS IN UPWELLING DUE TO GRADUALLY CHANGING FORCING; AND THIRD, A PREDICTION OF COASTAL UPWELLING IN A FUTURE WARM CLIMATE, OBTAINED BY FORCING A HIGH-RESOLUTION REGIONAL COASTAL OCEAN MODEL WITH COUPLED CLIMATE MODEL OUTPUT GENERATED FROM FUTURE CLIMATE CHANGE SCENARIOS OF THE COUPLED MODEL INTERCOMPARISON PROJECT PHASE 5 (CMIP5). THE PROPOSED STUDY WILL USE A RANGE OF SATELLITE PRODUCTS, INCLUDING BASIN-SCALE AND COASTAL SCATTEROMETER WIND PRODUCTS, SEA SURFACE TEMPERATURE, AND SEA SURFACE HEIGHT. THESE WILL FIRST BE USED FOR THE DEVELOPMENT OF A NEW PREDICTIVE UPWELLING INDEX AND FOR A STATISTICAL ANALYSIS OF THE RELATION BETWEEN ENSO AND COASTAL UPWELLING. THEN THE SATELLITE PRODUCTS WILL BE USED TO FORCE A HIGHRESOLUTION OCEAN MODEL OF THE U.S.~WEST COAST UPWELLING ZONE. ONCE THE MODEL PREDICTIONS OF UPWELLING RESPONSE TO CLIMATE VARIABILITY ARE TESTED USING THIS APPROACH, THE MODEL WILL BE DRIVEN WITH CMIP5 MODEL OUTPUT TO MAKE FUTURE PREDICTIONS. THE PROPOSED WORK HAS RELEVANCE TO OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE RESPONSE OF UPWELLING TO CLIMATE FORCING ON A RANGE OF TIME SCALES, FROM INTERANNUAL (ENSO-RELATED RESEARCH COMPONENT), TO FUTURE CLIMATE PREDICTIONS. IT MAY ALSO OFFER SOME INSIGHT INTO THE PROXY OBSERVATION OF THE WARMING OF UPWELLING SITES DURING PAST WARM CLIMATES. THUS THE PROJECT IS EXPECTED TO ENHANCE OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE DYNAMICS OF THE RESPONSE OF UPWELLING SYSTEMS TO CLIMATE CHANGE. IN ADDITION TO THIS SCIENTIFIC VALUE, THE PROPOSED WORK ADDRESSES A SUBJECT OF BROAD PRACTICAL IMPORTANCE, DUE TO THE ROLE OF UPWELLING IN SUPPORTING ECOSYSTEMS AND FISHERIES. FINALLY, THE WORK WILL FORM THE CORE OF A POSTDOCTORAL PROJECT AND THEREFORE SERVE AS A CRUCIAL DEVELOPMENTAL STEP IN THE CAREER OF AN EARLY-STAGE RESEARCHER.
